nodes.title: Visual Prompt Builder
widgets_values:
The green nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Positive Prompt, following a top to bottom order: Opening Modifiers + Type of Image + Image Subject + Image Style + Closing Modifiers.

Each green node offers a list of options, one per line, grouped according to their focus.

Each line is numbered from 0 to x. 
Line #0 is always empty. 

If you don't want a certain node to contribute to the Positive Prompt, be sure to select 0 for that node.

Once you have defined your prompt modifiers and styles, you probably only want to change the content of the Image Subject node.

--

The red nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Negative Prompt.

Modify your Negative Prompt by choosing the desired option in the Negative String and Negative Embeddings switches below. 

Notice that negative embeddings are added at the end of the negative prompt. If you prefer a different order, you'll have to manually write your negative prompt.

nodes.title: Prompt engineering with Llama 8B
widgets_values:
This group puts together a prompt for Stable Diffusion and can be plugged into the clothes design, the model design, and the scene designer. You can copy the whole block, or change the connections from the right hand side, as you see fit. The blue block shows what the model is producing. The random number generators allow mashing up of styles if you get stuck.

Remember, if you don't want to make cloths just change the input texts.

nodes.title: Negative Prompt
widgets_values:
When you generate an image you are actually generating two images, one for the positive, and one for the negative. If you set your CFG to 0 it will not use your positive prompt at all and you will see what image you are generating with the negative prompt.

The CFG is then determining how much to push your positive image away from the image you generated with the negative prompt.

If your negative prompt has "bad arm" it will generate a negative image with some form of arms, the CFG will then push your positive image away from anything resembling arms all together, making it difficult to generate "good arms".

it's much more useful to generate the opposite of what you want using the negative prompt. "bad arms" is not the negative of "good arms" because both of them contain arms, it is going to fight itself. Where "monochrome" is a valid negative if you want a vibrant, colorful image. Or "circles" is a valid negative if you want something geometric with sharp angles.

Again, use the negative you think you want with 0 CFG and then ask "is this the exact opposite of what I want, containing nothing at all that I want to keep?

From https://www.reddit.com/r/StableDiffusion/comments/18e9sio/negative_prompt_tips/

nodes.title: System Prompt / Custom Instructions (Generic)
widgets_values:
You are a caption generator. I'll pass you a text that describes an image and you need to improve it to generate a caption.

Identify the key elements of my text and enrich each of them by adding many details. Then, add some final words describing the high quality of the image.

For example, if I would pass the text "a yellow box sits on the table", you would identify and enrich "a yellow box", "sits", and "on the table".

To enrich the text I'll pass and generate the caption, you must STRICTLY follow these additional rules:

1. Do not comment on the task or write introductory text. For example, do not say things like "The image presents a yellow box sitting on a table..." or "In the image, a yellow box sits on a table..." or "Solution:". Just describe the image with something like "a yellow box sits on a table..."

2. DO NOT output anything except the enriched paragraph describing the image as a caption.

3. DO NOT capitalize the first letter of the paragraph.

4. End the paragraph WITHOUT a period.

5. the object you describe must be fully visible in the centre of the frame with space around it, without a human model, 

6. Literal, technical, detailed, visual descriptions of the object, without flourish or invective,
